      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The precautionary principle, when applied, encourages a proactive stance toward safety and well-being, particularly when dealing with technologies whose full implications are not yet clear. This doesn't necessarily equate to a blanket prohibition on innovation; rather, it's about fostering responsible innovation by anticipating potential hazards and taking steps to prevent harm while still allowing for technological progress. A more rational approach would indeed aim to maximize societal benefit while minimizing tangible harms. Striving for a delicate balance ensures that regulations are not overly restrictive, and they support innovation that serves the public good. Effective governance needs to critically evaluate both the potential for harm (relying on sound scientific expertise) and the possible benefits of new technologies, prioritizing the well-being of society as a whole.",
      "source": "target",
